{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17529707","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17529707"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:57:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:57:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14442"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14442","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14442"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.65,0.22,0.08,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7137"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110637"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7137","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7137"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2024-10-15T15:05:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-02T16:32:46+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2024-10-16T13:48:55+10:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-29 11:33:26"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14442"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"16466"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92882"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1111"},{"type":"tags","id":"2936"},{"type":"tags","id":"3180"},{"type":"tags","id":"3237"},{"type":"tags","id":"3275"},{"type":"tags","id":"4458"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17041"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18175"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18500"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41821"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92882"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110637","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110637"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with her husband five days after giving birth to her first child. She appears agitated and is expressing bizarre beliefs about her baby being possessed by evil spirits. Her husband reports that she has not slept for the past three nights and has been talking rapidly about saving the world. She has no significant medical history and was not taking any medications during pregnancy. On examination, she appears dishevelled with vital signs within normal limits. She is hypervigilant and her speech is pressured and difficult to interrupt. She denies any thoughts of harming herself or the baby, but her husband is concerned about her erratic behaviour.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Start lithium and allow the patient to go home with her husband","Admit to the mother-baby unit for close observation","Admit to the psychiatric ward without the baby","Prescribe olanzapine and arrange outpatient follow-up","Discharge home with increased support from community mental health team"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario presents a clear case of postpartum psychosis, a psychiatric emergency that requires immediate intervention due to the potential risk to both the mother and the infant. The most appropriate next step in management is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eadmit to the mother-baby unit for close observation\u003C/strong\u003E. This option prioritizes safety while maintaining the crucial mother-infant bond. It is very likely that this admission will be completed with the administration of an antipsychotic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrescribing olanzapine and arranging outpatient follow-up\u003C/strong\u003E is inadequate for the severity of this presentation. Postpartum psychosis requires intensive monitoring and treatment, which cannot be safely provided in an outpatient setting at this acute stage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdmitting to the psychiatric ward without the baby\u003C/strong\u003E is not ideal as it separates the mother from her infant during a critical bonding period. Mother-baby units are specifically designed to provide psychiatric care while supporting the mother-infant relationship.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDischarging home with increased support from community mental health team\u003C/strong\u003E does not provide the level of supervision and immediate intervention that may be necessary in postpartum psychosis. The risk of harm to either the mother or baby is too high for home management at this stage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStarting lithium and allowing the patient to go home with her husband\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate as it does not address the immediate safety concerns. While lithium may be part of the treatment plan, it requires careful monitoring and takes time to reach therapeutic levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdmission to a mother-baby unit allows for comprehensive psychiatric assessment, initiation of appropriate medication (likely an antipsychotic), close monitoring of the mother\u0027s mental state and behaviour, and support for infant care and bonding. It also provides an opportunity to educate and involve family members in the care plan, which is crucial for ongoing support and monitoring once the acute phase has passed. The multidisciplinary team can also assess for any underlying medical causes of the psychosis and manage any physical health needs of both mother and baby.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Postpartum psychosis requires urgent psychiatric assessment and often inpatient admission due to the high risk of harm to the mother and infant.","Safety planning in postpartum psychosis should prioritize the well-being of both the mother and the infant.","Involving family members in the care plan is crucial for ensuring ongoing support and monitoring."],"references":["Osborne LM. Recognizing and managing postpartum psychosis: a clinical guide for obstetric providers. Obstetrics and Gynecology Clinics. 2018 Sep 1;45(3):455-68."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92882"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14442"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92882"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-02T16:32:39+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-02T16:32:58+09:30","number":4,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":null,"plagiarismScore":null,"plagiarismReportUrl":null},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7137"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110637"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9"}},"generation":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"ta